Thomas O. Ryder - Pay Pals - The Huffington Post















 Submit Correction








Pay Pals


CEO pay is determined by a company’s board of directors. Those directors are compensated for the time they spend shaping the company’s strategy. Here’s what the Fortune 100  executives paid each other from 2008 to 2012.



 Submit Correction



Find a director



















Thomas O. Ryder





Share on Facebook
Share on Twitter












Thomas O. Ryder



Between 2008 and 2012 he made
$1,227,694
as a director, more than 60% of all directors





Paid CEOs an average of
$1,681,840
in the last year of his directorship, more than 5% of all directors





Increased  CEO pay by an average of 
$400,000
between 2008 and 2012, more than 48% of all directors





Shares of his companies  increased  by
163.1%
between 2008 and 2012, better performance than 99% of all directors







The Thomas O. Ryder Stock Index










From January 2008 to December 2012, if you bought shares in companies when Thomas O. Ryder joined the board, and sold them when he left, you would have a 163.1 percent return on your investment, compared to a -2.8 percent return from the S&P 500.










Thomas O. Ryder's companies
Amazon.com
Nov. 1, 2002 to July 26, 2016

                Other board members at Amazon.com during this time were
                Alain Monié, Blake G. Krikorian, Jamie Gorelick and 8 more.Alain Monié, Blake G. Krikorian, Jamie Gorelick, Jeffrey P. Bezos, John Seely Brown, Jonathan J. Rubinstein, L. John Doerr, Myrtle S. Potter, Patricia Q. Stonesifer, Tom A. Alberg and William B. Gordon.





His Yearly  Compensation 




Yearly Payments to CEOs







                MEDIAN
              











Stock Performance is the difference between a director's stock index and the S&P 500.
A director's stock index is an unweighted index of company stock performances while they sat on the board.
CEO pay includes salary, bonuses, stock sales, and other payments.
Average CEO Pay is calculated using the last year a director sat on the board of each company.
Stock returns do not include dividends.
All directors refers to people who sat on the board of at least one Fortune 100 company between 2008 and 2012.


          The Pay Pals project relies on financial research conducted by the Center for Economic Policy and Research.
        
Sources: Google Finance, Yahoo Finance,
    Amazon.com SEC filings (2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012).
    
By Shane Shifflett, Jay Boice, Hilary Fung and Aaron Bycoffe





